pr_title: Allow evaluating FE functions at arbitrary points
pr_body:
I'm looking for feedback, in particular:

- I'm using my existing package [`Bernstein.jl`](https://github.com/eschnett/Bernstein.jl), but only call a single function in it. Should I instead import the respective code?
- What mechanism should I use to cache the calculated `kdtree`? Can I somehow attach it to the triangulation?
- Where is @ericneiva's branch that is mentioned in https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/issues/425?
- Did I overlook some existing functionality that would simplify my code?

I'm aware that the code is still quite restrictive (only handles `SingleFieldFEFunction`s with simplicial meshes), and that it uses linear interpolation instead of actually evaluating the basis functions.

Will eventually close https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/issues/425, I hope.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 564908476, 'comment_body': 'We could probably encapsulate this code in a function and do dispatching with respect to the triangulation type. The code below is for an unstructured (simplicial) mesh. We could also consider the case for a structured Cartesian mesh (which is much easier, no tree involved).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 1, 26, 23, 27, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'santiagobadia', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 564909901, 'comment_body': 'We have to decide what happens if the point is in more than once cell. We can provide just one of the cells. The result is going to be identical for C0 spaces. For discontinuous spaces, the query is ill-posed (the function is not defined at this point) and we would just return the function in one of the cells.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 1, 26, 23, 31, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'santiagobadia', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 565013348, 'comment_body': "I am calculating the distance from the point to all the cells. Without round-off, and with non-overlapping cells, the distance would be positive for exactly one cell and negative for all other ones. (I should probably change my sign convention.) Due to round-off, the distance can be slightly positive or slightly negative for points near cell boundaries, in particular near vertices. In this case, I choose the cell with the largest distance, and I check that the distance (if negative) is at most at round-off level.

I'll update the comments in the code.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 1, 27, 4, 8, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'eschnett', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 565018350, 'comment_body': 'I think that there is the (unlikely) possibility that the distance will be zero (or in the round-off error) for some cells, am I wrong? I was thinking of cells as closed domains, which is the standard definition in finite elements. If you consider that cells are open domains, you can find points that do not belong to any cell. At the end is just `<` vs `<=`, etc.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 1, 27, 4, 21, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'santiagobadia', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 565018835, 'comment_body': 'In any case, what you propose is resilient to this, so keep it as it is', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 1, 27, 4, 23, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'santiagobadia', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 565351462, 'comment_body': "I view the cells as closed as well, and would be happy to return a value from any one of the cells if the point lies on the boundary. The problem I'm addressing here is only round-off error, which is a real, practical problem. For example, asking for the value at a vertex can yield distances that say the point is outside of all the neighbouring cells.

For the cases I tested, this error can be more than 100 eps, but was always less than 1000 eps. This distance is in terms of the barycentric coordinates which have a range of 0...1. In this case, the code will extrapolate from one of the cells by that distance, i.e. about 1e-12 of a cell width.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 1, 27, 14, 28, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'eschnett', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 642223647, 'comment_body': 'Remove this line, so that `InverseFieldsTests.jl` is included only once', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 31, 5, 44, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'fverdugo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 642225346, 'comment_body': 'Why do you need to implement this here in `src/MultiField/MultiFieldCellFields.jl` ? I would say this should go in `src/CellData/CellFields.jl`. The implementation of the evaluation of a `CellField` in some `Points` is conceptually decoupled from FE spaces,multifield etc. It just needs the `CellField` interface and some of the upstream modules.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 31, 5, 49, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'fverdugo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 642225712, 'comment_body': 'As with the implementation, I would move the tests into `test/CellDataTests/CellFieldsTests.jl`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 31, 5, 50, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'fverdugo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 642790940, 'comment_body': 'I think the changes in this file are no longer needed after moving the code to `CellFields.jl`. Can you revert them?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 1, 5, 27, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'fverdugo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 642791054, 'comment_body': 'Remove this line', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 1, 5, 28, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'fverdugo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 643931062, 'comment_body': "You are exporting `point_to_cell!` but the function to generate its cache object seems to be private.

Here, there are 2 options:

1. Do not export `point_to_cell!` and rename it to  `_point_to_cell!` so that it is clear that it's private.
2.  Make public  also the mechanism to generate the cache. In this case, follow the API of the abstract type `Map` just to be consistent with other parts of the code. 
```julia
struct PointToCellMap{T<:Triangulation} <: Map
  trian::T
end

return_cache(k::PointToCellMap,x::Point) = ...
evaluate!(cache,k::PointToCellMap,x::Point) = ...
```



 ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 12, 52, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'fverdugo', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body:
Hi @santiagobadia, @ericneiva, @oriolcg and @eschnett 

I am submitting a pull request after adding some more tests for `evaluate`. So far I have added test for:

- Hypercubes and Simplices.
- Evaluating at a random vertex.
- Evaluating at a random point on the face.
- Evaluation using `CellPoint`. I might require some feedback for this. I had to export `make_inverse_table`, `point_to_cell!` and `distance` from the implementation. I then use these functions for generating the `cell_to_point` map again, and pass the result to `CellPoint` and then to `evaluate`.

pr_title: Evaluate any monomial basis at single point
pr_body:
Hi @fverdugo 

Here is the PR to add the feature to evaluate any monomial basis at a single point. @ericneiva mentioned you are on vacation, so you can have a look at it whenever you get back! ð

pr_body:
Hi @fverdugo @ericneiva @santiagobadia @oriolcg 

Thanks for all your help on this. This is the PR for adding the features and tests for interpolation. It contains the following:

- Interpolation for Lagrange elements
   - Modify [`nlsolve`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-bc3363c18bc44705ccecd90e660de61b29b61a46cd8b2e36f8b80b78715b0676) to Newton Raphson and Backtracking to handle distorted meshes a little better.
   - New method [`evaluate!`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-c7da292305a713b492f2b300da27a9300557c50a936e542977ff02334c50c5a1R128) for `LagrangianDofBasis`.
- Interpolation for RT elements
   - New method [`evaluate!`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-ba506509a89b9ff975762ef98f39e3dd9a7d0ef2b6fdb3b962576fd48abdd161R330) for `MomentBasedDofBasis`.
- New method for [`_cell_vals`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-bc1da514f64e061186945f971caeded33d6b9e554e8f7f001dca0a1d1f0b6496R309) to generate cell-wise dof values.
- New method for [`CellField`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-bc1da514f64e061186945f971caeded33d6b9e554e8f7f001dca0a1d1f0b6496R302) to generate the `GenericCellField` object for non-compatible triangulations.
- New method [`interpolate_everywhere_non_compatible_trian`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-bc1da514f64e061186945f971caeded33d6b9e554e8f7f001dca0a1d1f0b6496R342) to generate the `FEFunction`. Also implemented for [`::MultiFieldFESpace`](https://github.com/gridap/Gridap.jl/compare/master...Balaje:interpolate_everywhere_arbitrary_points#diff-4656649d9f7084f62529b5ecaa571623e1bd4490e5063a0ad97bd9a3e4d0424dR419).

The only thing @ericneiva mentioned was whether to have `evaluate!(cache, b::LagrangianDofBasis, field, points)` separately from the original implementation of `evaluate!(cache, b::LagrangianDofBasis, field)` or have `points` as an optional argument. 

The PR is not urgent @fverdugo @ericneiva. Please have a look at it whenever you are free. Thanks ð
